'''Charles William Wentworth Fitzwilliam, 3rd Earl Fitzwilliam in the peerage of England, and 5th Earl Fitzwilliam in the peerage of Ireland''' {{post-nominals|KG}} (4 May 1786 – 4 October 1857) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] nobleman.  He was President three times of the [[Royal Statistical Society]] in 1838–40, 1847–49, and 1853–5{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}; and President of the [[British Association for the Advancement of Science]] in its inaugural year (1831–2).

Before inheriting the Earldom on 8 February 1833 on the death of his father, he was known by the [[courtesy title]] of '''Viscount Milton'''. Under that name he was the [[British Whig Party|Whig]] Member of Parliament for [[Northamptonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Northamptonshire]] between 1831 and 1832.

He married the Hon. Mary Dundas (30 May 1787 – 1 November 1830) on 8 July 1806; she was his cousin and the daughter of [[Thomas Dundas, 1st Baron Dundas]] and Lady Charlotte Fitzwilliam, the [[William Fitzwilliam, 2nd Earl Fitzwilliam|2nd and 4th Earl]]'s sister. He was succeeded by his second son [[William Wentworth-Fitzwilliam, 6th Earl Fitzwilliam|William]].

